x4freetext: The deuteron beam was accelerated by
way of the model FN Tandem Van de Graaff accelerator
The target used for this experiment consisted of a
6.86 g rectangular 238U foil (3.65 x 5.20 x 0.02 cm)
backed by rectangular foils of 99.5% natural iron
with thickness of 0.0038 cm and positioned in the
neutron beam 215 cm downstream from the gas cell.
. Gamma rays emitted from the target were
measured using a set of clover and planer HPGe
detectors, each equipped with a bismuth germinate
suppression shield and NaI nose cone. The detectors
were mounted on movable stands that rotated about
the target position in the horizontal plane and
allowed measurements at laboratory angles ranging
from 0. to 140 deg.
Time of flight was used to separate prompt
gamma rays.
Fast neutrons were produced via the 2H(d,n)3He
reaction by bombarding a deuterium gas cell with an
accelerated beam of deuterons.The system provide up
to 3 mu-A of pulsed deuteron current with a pulse
width of 2 ns and a repetition rate of 2.5 MHz or
smaller (by factors of 2).The deuteron beam was
accelerated by way of the model FN Tandem Van de
Graaff accelerator before bombarding a cylindrical
gas cell pressurized to 7.8 atm with 99.999% pure
deuterium gas.Deuteron ions entered the cell through
a 6.35 mu-m Havar foil.
Statistical uncertainty
Total systematic unceratinty was calculated from
systematic uncertainties in
neutron flux determination
internal conversion coeficient of measured
radiation
gamma ray detection efficiency
238U sample mass
